HEADWORD: Eurythmy
<hw>Eu"ryth*my</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>eurythmia</ets>, Gr. <?/; <grk>e'y^</grk> well + <?/ rhythm,
measure, proportion, symmetry: cf. F. <ets>eurythmie</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Fine Arts)</fld> <def>Just or harmonious proportion or
movement, as in the composition of a poem, an edifice, a painting, or a
statue.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>Regularly of the pulse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eusebian</ent>⟦br⟧
